  "id": "",
  "summary": "Hidden clipboard exfiltration to hardcoded Telegram bot in bittensor-burn-monitor",
  "details": "Package advertises itself as a Bittensor subnet burn-rate monitor but ships a compiled clipboard-monitoring daemon (bittensor_burn_watch/core.cpython-310-*.so) that is auto-loaded from __init__.py and unconditionally exfiltrates the user's clipboard contents to an attacker-controlled Telegram bot. The wheel bundles bittensor_burn_watch/defaults.env containing a hardcoded TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN (8666228137:AAF_NLMrow4cDf3uEJCl3JY7DeBHtovd1TU) and TELEGRAM_CHAT_ID (8766781014); the file's own header states 'Bundled for all pip install users.' The compiled daemon reads the clipboard on Windows (Win32 API with a PowerShell fallback that uses 'no window flash'), macOS, and Linux (auto-installing wl-clipboard/xclip via apt/dnf/pacman without prompting), holds an exclusive lock so only one poller runs, and POSTs each unique copied string to api.telegram.org for the bundled bot/chat. Cross-platform persistence is established via Windows Task Scheduler, a Linux systemd user service, and a macOS LaunchAgent with KeepAlive plus a 15-minute watchdog. The clipboard-logging behavior, the Telegram destination, and the persistence are not mentioned in the README, and the.pyx sources are omitted from the wheel so only the compiled.so contains the logic — intentional concealment. Targeting Bittensor (TAO) users, whose clipboards routinely carry wallet seed phrases, mnemonics, and exchange credentials, makes this a high-value credential and key-material stealer.",
